Let’s take Casey in his leg lift, Tim’s
already in his leg lift when this footage

00:00:25.245 --> 00:00:36.854
starts, both in a good position, doing a good
job of lifting up and then leading forward

00:00:36.854 --> 00:00:42.104
and taking those hips to the target.

00:00:42.104 --> 00:00:47.354
As Casey’s going he’s taking that knee
with him, so this is a great first move here,

00:00:47.354 --> 00:00:53.505
you can see Tim’s in a similar position,
as his lift leg comes down both very similar.

00:00:53.505 --> 00:01:00.755
Let’s see what Tim does from here, you can
see he continues to load down as he takes

00:01:00.755 --> 00:01:06.544
the ankle to knee as best as he can to his
front hip, takes that force vector into linear

00:01:06.544 --> 00:01:07.964
position.

00:01:07.964 --> 00:01:11.925
This is tough for young pitchers to get down
and build this much flexion at a young age

00:01:11.925 --> 00:01:18.955
because our leg strength doesn’t show up
until we get to High School, College, so to

00:01:18.955 --> 00:01:24.805
show some leg strength at a young age is pretty
impressive, it’s impressive that little

00:01:24.805 --> 00:01:28.606
Tim is doing this but this is the goal here.

00:01:28.606 --> 00:01:33.894
We wanna make sure that we’re moving down,
building flexion as we’re lining up the

00:01:33.894 --> 00:01:39.885
force vector, the ankle knee and staying closed
and this is what Tim’s doing here, not as

00:01:39.885 --> 00:01:42.924
well as he does today but incredibly well
for his age.

00:01:42.924 --> 00:01:51.335
We can see here with Casey, this brings up
a great point of what I talk about in my analysis,

00:01:51.335 --> 00:02:03.035
you can see Casey did a great job in getting
to this first move but he doesn’t take advantage

00:02:03.035 --> 00:02:10.955
of it and he allows his front leg to open
up, all his weight to go forward and for him

00:02:10.955 --> 00:02:17.015
to land with a stiff drive leg, he never used
the drive leg to build power.

00:02:17.015 --> 00:02:28.645
The reason we lead with the hip, we start
our movement early, we take that drive leg

00:02:28.645 --> 00:02:39.045
knee with the front hip is because we want
to put ourselves in a position to start building

00:02:39.045 --> 00:02:46.595
speed, preventing the lift leg from opening
early so that we can get into this position

00:02:46.595 --> 00:02:48.795
that Tim is in.

00:02:48.795 --> 00:02:54.066
If this lift leg had flung open earlier and
you didn’t lead with the hip and you didn’t

00:02:54.066 --> 00:02:58.955
take that force vector with it, you would
never even be able to have the potential to

00:02:58.955 --> 00:03:06.545
get where Tim is so the reason for this is
to get to this – flexion of the drive leg

00:03:06.545 --> 00:03:12.675
knee, force vector, as linear as you can,
you need this knee pointing to that target,

00:03:12.675 --> 00:03:16.575
as linear as you can.

00:03:16.575 --> 00:03:20.285
Let me draw lines so you can see.

00:03:20.285 --> 00:03:26.665
You want this force vector right there, so
that would be your ankle, and knee, and then

00:03:26.665 --> 00:03:29.735
your front hip out here, that’s where we
wanna get.

00:03:29.735 --> 00:03:35.605
Tim is almost there, his force vector is just
a little vertical because that’s his front

00:03:35.605 --> 00:03:37.405
hip there.

00:03:37.405 --> 00:03:45.785
So we wanna get all the way down her and out
here, that’s why we start with this move,

00:03:45.785 --> 00:03:50.025
